@* Sized array new T[n] (BENCH n°41, decision 122): a `new int[3]` maps to `new Array(3).fill(0)` -- C#'s
   n-defaults array (int->0). `xs` starts as new int[3] = [0,0,0] (Length 3, xs[0] = 0); #fill REASSIGNS it to
   a literal array new int[]{7,8,9,10} (Length 4, xs[0] = 7). So #len goes "3" -> "4" and #first "0" -> "7",
   exactly as Blazor renders the same C# array. xs is read by @xs.Length/@xs[0] AND reassigned by Fill -> a
   signal; its wholesale reassignment fires the effect (an element write xs[i]=v would be refused). *@

<p>Len: <span id="len">@xs.Length</span>, First: <span id="first">@xs[0]</span></p>

<button id="fill" @onclick="Fill">fill</button>

@code {
    private int[] xs = new int[3];

    private void Fill()
    {
        xs = new int[] { 7, 8, 9, 10 };
    }
}
